<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-575-871  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 575 871.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  Oct 25 1990 v16 n22 p12(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Plesman Publications Ltd. (Canada) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Mixed signals. (editorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Slofstra, Martin.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer IndustryIndustry AnalysisFuture of ComputingTrends.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Mixed signalsandM;Is the computer industry slowing down?andM;All indications show the country has headed into a recession.andP;  With majorcutbacks already announced at very large Canadian companies such as AirCanada and Imperial Oil, can downsizing of their computer operations be farbehind?andM;Well, maybe not.andM;Many will tell you that the computer industry is insulated from the effectsof a recession.andP;  After all, companies can use information technology to cutcosts and increase efficiency.andP;  But just how far can anyone stretch that lineof logic?andM;From an industry point of view, the signals are mixed.andM;Take the recently-released Evans Report on The Top 100 Computer Companies inCanada (See story, p. 1).andP;  Most industry sectors, with the notable exceptionof services, show declines in growth rates from the previous year.andP;  You canexpect that when the results for fiscal 1990 come in, that decline willbecome more pronounced.andM;Also, the mediocre results of companies including DEC, Unisys, Systemhouse,Wang, Data General, Newbridge, Gandalf and Kinburn have all been welldocumented in these pages in recent months.andM;Don't jump to conclusions too quickly.andP;  For every company that isexperiencing a downturn, several continue to fly high or mount impressivecomebacks -- NCR, Microsoft, Compaq, Geac and Cognos -- just to name a few.andM;One good sign may be the unusually high number and impressive quality of mostof the product announcements -- from laptops all the way up to mainframes.andM;But the product introduction frenzy can be interpreted in two ways.andP;  Dovendors legitimately see lucrative short-term market opportunities or arethey pushing the panict button?andM;Is the industry slowing down or thriving?andP;  Can you expect the axe to fall onyour budget in the coming year?andM;Your guess is as good as ours.andO;</TEXT></DOC>